1. Project Introduction¶

  • Apply the concepts learned from the lessons in Data Wrangling, to gather data from a variety of sources and in a variety of formats, assess its quality and tidiness, then clean it. Showcase data wrangling efforts through analyses and visualizations.
  • Gather data from 3 sources:
    • WeRateDogs Twitter archive twitter_archive_enhanced.csv. This contains 5000+ basic tweet data about dog rating, name, and "stage"
    • tweet image predictions image-predictions.tsv. This file contains dog breed prediction results (from a Neural Network classifier) for every dog images from the WeRateDogs Twitter archive.
    • Twitter API tweepy. Use this API to query additional data (in JSON format) for each tweet ID in the WeRateDogs Twitter archive. Given some tweet IDs in the WeRateDogs Twitter archive no longer exist in Twitter, we will just try the API call to practice data gathering concept and then use Udacity provided equivalent data set tweet_json.txt for completing this project.
  • After gathering the data, assess them visually and programmatically for quality and tidiness issues. Detect and document at least eight (8) quality issues and two (2) tidiness issues.
  • Clean each of the issues identified, document the cleaning steps taken and store the results to a clean and tidy master pandas DataFrame.
  • Analyze and visualize the wrangled data to produce at least three (3) insights and one (1) visualization
  • Produce a 300-600 word written report with brief description of the wrangling efforts, frame it as an internal document. Create another 250-word-minimum written report to communicate the insights and displays the visualization(s) produced from the wrangled data. Frame it as an external document, like a blog post or magazine article

2. Data Wrangling¶

This process entails the following:

  • Gather the 3 required datasets from different sources load into 3 dataframes
  • Inspect the 3 dataframes visually and programmatically to assess the tidiness and quality of the data
  • Compose a data cleaning do-do list from assessment results for use in Data Cleansing

# For project submission, set api keys to '*'
# setup twitter api auth

consumer_key = '*'
consumer_secret = '*'
access_token = '*'
access_secret = '*'

for k in [consumer_key, consumer_secret, access_token, access_secret]:
    skip = False if len(k) > 1 else True
    
if skip:    
    print('In project submission ... skip Twitter API Call practice')
else:
    auth = tweepy.OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
    auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_secret)

    api = tweepy.API(auth_handler=auth, 
                 wait_on_rate_limit= True,
                 wait_on_rate_limit_notify=True)

    print_ok = 100
    print_err = 4
    # get all the tweet ids from twdf (twitter_archive_enhanced.csv)
    twids = twdf.tweet_id.values

    # start reading 
    start = timer()
    tw_dict = {}
    baddict = {}
    cnt = 0

    for id in twids:
        cnt +=1
        try:
            txt = api.get_status(id, tweet_mode='extended')
            # convert id to str as json.dump require dict key to be string
            tw_dict[str(id)] = txt._json       
            if cnt % print_ok == 0:
                print('Success:{}-{}'.format(cnt, id))
        except tweepy.TweepError as e:
            baddict[str(id)] = e
            if cnt % print_err == 0:
                print('tweepErr:{}-{}'.format(id, e))
            pass

    elapsed = timer() - start
    print('\nTwitter read done. Total elapsed time: {} minutes'.format(elapsed/60))
    
    with open('twt2_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:  
        json.dump(tw_dict, outfile, 
                  ensure_ascii = True,
                  sort_keys = True,
                  indent=4)
    
    twtdf = pd.read_json('twt2_json.txt',orient='index')
    print('\ntwtdf.shape:', twtdf.shape)
    twtdf.to_csv('twt_df.csv', index = False)

    print('\ntweepErr dict:\n',baddict)
    baddf=pd.DataFrame(list(baddict.items()), columns=['twid', 'msg'])
    print('\nbaddf.shape:', baddf.shape, '\n')
    baddf.to_csv('tweet_nodat.csv', index = False)
    baddf

import tweepy
from tweepy import OAuthHandler
import json
from timeit import default_timer as timer

# Query Twitter API for each tweet in the Twitter archive and save JSON in a text file
# These are hidden to comply with Twitter's API terms and conditions
consumer_key = 'HIDDEN'
consumer_secret = 'HIDDEN'
access_token = 'HIDDEN'
access_secret = 'HIDDEN'

auth = OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_secret)

api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit=True)

# NOTE TO STUDENT WITH MOBILE VERIFICATION ISSUES:
# df_1 is a DataFrame with the twitter_archive_enhanced.csv file. You may have to
# change line 17 to match the name of your DataFrame with twitter_archive_enhanced.csv
# NOTE TO REVIEWER: this student had mobile verification issues so the following
# Twitter API code was sent to this student from a Udacity instructor
# Tweet IDs for which to gather additional data via Twitter's API
tweet_ids = df_1.tweet_id.values
len(tweet_ids)

# Query Twitter's API for JSON data for each tweet ID in the Twitter archive
count = 0
fails_dict = {}
start = timer()
# Save each tweet's returned JSON as a new line in a .txt file
with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
    # This loop will likely take 20-30 minutes to run because of Twitter's rate limit
    for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
        count += 1
        print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id))
        try:
            tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
            print("Success")
            json.dump(tweet._json, outfile)
            outfile.write('\n')
        except tweepy.TweepError as e:
            print("Fail")
            fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
            pass
end = timer()
print(end - start)
print(fails_dict)

Read tweet_json.txt and load into dataframe. Entries pertaining to re-tweets or reply to tweets should not be loaded given the focus is on original tweets.¶

In [6]:
tw2df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['tweet_id', 'retwt_cnt', 'fav_cnt'])

# open the TXT file programmatically
with open('tweet_json.txt') as f:
    for line in f:
        # load its contents line by line, i.e. JSON object by JSON object
        twt = json.loads(line)
        # skip retweet or reply to tweet
        if ((twt['in_reply_to_status_id'] == None) & (twt['in_reply_to_user_id'] == None)): 
            id_str = twt['id_str']
            retwt_cnt = twt['retweet_count']
            fav_cnt = twt['favorite_count']
            
            # store the additional needed information into a dataframe
            tw2df = tw2df.append({'tweet_id' : id_str,
                                  'retwt_cnt' : retwt_cnt,
                                  'fav_cnt' : fav_cnt}, 
                                  ignore_index = True)
        else:
            continue

2.3 Data Cleansing Tasks¶

Summary of data quality and tidiness issues:

Quality issues¶

  • Enhanced Twitter Archive (twdf)
    • tweet_id 835246439529840640 (index 313) has incorrect rating numerator and 0 denominator value, needs to be corrected to the original rating 13/10.
    • six rating numerators are not correctly extracted, need to be corrected.
    • tweet_id 835152434251116546 & 746906459439529985 (index 315 & 1016) have 0 rating. These two rows can be omitted without impacting our analysis.
    • rating_numerator and rating_denominator should be in float to accommodate fractional numerators.
    • tweet_id needs to be converted from interger to string.
    • timestamp needs to be converted from string format to actual timestamp format.
    • invalid dog names e.g. 'a', 'The', 'an' need to be corrected, set them to 'None'.
    • missing favorite count and retweet count which are important for our analysis, obtain the missing information. from Additional Twitter data (twdf2).
    • in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_user_id and source columns are duplicated in Additional Twitter API data (twdf2). They are not needed for the analysis so can be dropped.
    • retweeted_status_id, retweeted_status_user_id, retweeted_status_timestamp columns can be dropped since our analysis is only focusing on original tweets.
    • expanded_urls column is superfluous, can be dropped.
  • Image Predictions (imgdf)
    • p1, p2 and p3 have inconsistent dog names, with a mixtures of underscore, hypen, space. The naming convention should be standardized for data consistency.
    • tweet_id needs to be converted from interger to string

Tidiness Issues¶

  • Enhanced Twitter Archive (twdf)
    • dog stages are represented in 4 different columns ('doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo'), they should be combined into a single column.
  • Image Predictions (imgdf)
    • p1_dog, p2_dog and p3_dog columns contain non, partial and true dog breed predictions, representing 3 types of observations in the same table. Need a new column to clearly identify the 3 observations.
  • All 3 datasets (Enhanced Twitter Archive, Image Predictions and Additional Twitter API data) can be combined into a single dataset for efficient accessing

In [46]:
def dog_stage_cnt(row):
    stage_cnt = row[['doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo']].count().sum()
    
    if (stage_cnt > 1):
        return 'multiple'
    else:
        if (row.doggo == row.doggo):
            return 'doggo'
        elif (row.floofer == row.floofer):
            return 'floofer'
        elif (row.pupper == row.pupper):
            return 'pupper'
        elif (row.puppo == row.puppo):
            return 'puppo'
    return pd.np.nan

twdf['dog_stage'] = twdf.apply(lambda row: dog_stage_cnt(row), axis = 1)

The dog and hybrid share the same rating of 13 while the not dog has a rating of 10, which rank 4th and 2nd respectively in the top 10 dog ratings. Both the dog and hybrid are actually Labrador Retriever which ranks 3rd in the top 10 dog breeds. The not dog was misclassified but is actually a Spanish Water Dog, though the breed is not among the top 10 dog breeds.¶

So of the 1971 entries in the twitter_archive_master dataset, 305 entries were misclassified as not dog, 472 as hybrid (i.e. may be dog). Only 1194 were correctly classified as dog yet none attains the highest p1 predection of 1. Ironically, the not dog has the highest prediction confidence of 1.¶

The numbers represent a 60.58% (=1194/1971 x 100%) chance the model correctly identifies a dog as a dog. Obviously, the model has more room for improvement.¶

4. Conclusion¶

We went through Data Wrangling process by

  • firstly gathering data from a variety of on and offline sources and in a variety of formats. The main dataset Enhance Twitter Archive which is provisioned by Udacity, contains dog ratings from the popular Twitter WeRateDogs rating provider. However, it was missing important elements like favorite and retweet counts, which fortunately can be scraped from Twitter site via an API provisioned by Twitter. Nonetheless, Twitter site is constantly aging out old tweets, so some of the required entries are no longer available for scrapping. To get around this, we resorted to loading an archived version of Twitter dataset tweet_json.txt provisioned by Udacity. Udacity also provisioned another dataset Image Predictions File that can be used to run every image from the Enhance Twitter Archive to get the top 3 predictions of the dog breed, providing the image is not older than August 1, 2017.
  • secondly assessing the data visually and programmatically to identify potential data tidiness and quality issues that would be preventing any meaningful data insight analysis from happening. All the issues identified are documented in a list for cleaning.
  • thirdly cleaning the data issues documented. Each issue was prescribed a code fix, followed by execution and testing of the code fix.
  • Forthly, combining the 3 cleansed datasets into one single master dataset and storing it to a csv file and a python SQL database.
  • Lastly, loading the master dataset and conducting various data insight analysis and visualization on the wrangled data to produce a report documenting the wrangling effort and another, communicating 3 insights (pertaining to favorite and retweet counts with respect to time, classification of dog species, and performance of the dog image classifier) along with related visualizations to compliment the insights.
